[[File:Byron_letter.jpg|thumb|A short note to [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]]]
'''The letters of [[Lord Byron]]''', of which about 3,000 are known, range in date from 1798, when Byron was 10 years old, to 9 April 1824, a few days before he died.{{sfn|Marchand|1973|p=39}}{{sfn|Marchand|1981|pp=152-154}}  They have long received extraordinary critical praise for their wit, spontaneity and sincerity.  Many rate Byron as the greatest letter-writer in English literature,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weeks |first1=Edward |date=1949 |title=The Peripatetic Reviewer |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5qkGAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Byron+is+rated+the+greatest+letter%22&dq=%22Byron+is+rated+the+greatest+letter%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjxwK7no6jYAhUGUlAKHeJZACAQ6AEIKTAA |journal=Atlantic Monthly |volume=183 |page=76 |access-date=26 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Foot |first1=Michael |author-link1=Michael Foot |year=1988 |title=The Politics of Paradise: A Vindication of Byron |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=70laAAAAMAAJ&q=%22would+make+him+the+greatest+letter-writer+in+the+language%22&dq=%22would+make+him+the+greatest+letter-writer+in+the+language%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcu8KEpKjYAhWOPFAKHWNsAhwQ6AEIKTAA |location=London |publisher=Collins |page=100 |isbn=0002172550 |access-date=26 December 2017 }}</ref>{{sfn|Lansdown|2015|p=xxiii}} and consider his letters comparable or superior to his poems as literary achievements.<ref>{{cite news |last=Donoghue |first=Denis |author-link=Denis Donoghue (academic) |date=14 April 2016 |title=Review of ''Byron's Letters and Journals: A New Selection'' |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/byron-s-letters-and-journals-a-new-selection-review-1.2610744 |work=The Irish Times |location=Dublin |access-date=26 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |year=2011 |orig-year=1922 |editor1-last=Murray |editor1-first=John |title=Lord Byron's Correspondence. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WaqNh_4ilbYC&pg=PR10&dq=%22now+equal+to+that+which+he+has+long+enjoyed%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyuovEqajYAhUNb1AKHWZICSUQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22now%20equal%20to%20that%20which%20he%20has%20long%20enjoyed%22&f=false |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=x |isbn=9781108033947 |access-date=26 December 2017 }}</ref>{{sfn|Marchand|1981|p=1}}  They have also been called "one of the three great informal autobiographies in English", alongside the diaries of [[Samuel Pepys]] and [[James Boswell]].{{sfn|Lansdown|2015|p=xi}}  Their literary value is reflected in the huge prices collectors will pay for them; in 2009 a sequence of 15 letters to his friend [[Francis Hodgson]] was sold at auction for almost £280,000.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Byron's letters get nearly USD 460,000 at UK auction |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/Byronrsquos-letters-get-nearly-USD-460000-at-UK-auction/article16889324.ece |work=The Hindu |location=Chennai |date=30 October 2009 |access-date=26 December 2017 }}</ref>

==Analysis==

Although in his letters Byron adapted his style and stance to his different correspondents,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nicholson |first1=Andrew |year=2004 |chapter=Byron's Prose |editor1-last=Bone |editor1-first=Drummond |editor1-link=Drummond Bone |title=The Cambridge Companion to Byron |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZtSF3PrMtNoC&pg=PA191&dq=%22crucial+and+rudimentary%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjp67bYiarYAhUEL1AKHdcVCB8Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22crucial%20and%20rudimentary%22&f=false |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=191-192 |isbn=0521781469 |access-date=27 December 2007 }}</ref> they all share an unstudied, unliterary appearance, an "offhand eloquence", which at its best resembles the talk of a conversationalist of genius.{{sfn|Quennell|1990|p=x}}<ref>{{cite book |year=1984 |editor1-last=Graham |editor1-first=Peter W. |title=Byron's Bulldog: The Letters of John Cam Hobhouse to Lord Byron |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7U-1AAAAIAAJ&q=%22offhand+eloquence%22+inauthor:graham&dq=%22offhand+eloquence%22+inauthor:graham&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi016eg85jYAhXQhrQKHQTnDNUQ6AEIKTAA |location=Columbus |publisher=Ohio State University Press |page=3 |isbn=0814203671 |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  He never wrote to produce an effect.{{sfn|Maurois|1936|p=xii}}  [[Thomas Babington Macaulay|Lord Macaulay]], in one of [[Critical and Historical Essays (Macaulay)|his essays]], wrote that Byron's letters "are less affected than those of [[Alexander Pope|Pope]] and [[Horace Walpole|Walpole]], [and] have more matter in them than those of [[William Cowper|Cowper]]"; if literary art was employed it was "that highest art which cannot be distinguished from nature".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Macaulay |first1=Thomas Babington |year=1843 |title=Critical and Historical Essays. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=35oiLioJ5KsC&pg=PA312&dq=%22admirable+instance+of+that+highest+art%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpvIfZm6rYAhWSYVAKHQD_ByMQ6AEIWjAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=London |publisher=Longman, Brown, Green, and Longmans |page=312 |access-date=27 November 2017 }}</ref>  All are deeply imbued with his volatile and indefinable personality, which, for those who find his personality offensive, can be something of a disadvantage.{{sfn|Quennell|1990|pp=viii-ix}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Sampson |first=Fiona |author-link=Fiona Sampson |date=16 June 2015 |title=What's not to like about this selection? Just its author… |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/byrons-letters-and-journals-a-new-selection-edited-by-richard-lansdown-book-review-whats-not-to-like-10324661.html |work=The Independent |location=London |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  They are marked by rapid alternations of mood,{{sfn|Lansdown|2015|p=xiii}} by common sense, wit, intellect and sincerity,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Symons |first1=Arthur |author-link1=Arthur Symons |year=1909 |title=The Romantic Movement in English Poetry |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4klAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA253&dq=%22wit+their+clear+and+defiant%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjz8P6QoarYAhWGmbQKHXdQBxwQ6AEIPjAE |location=New York |publisher=E. P. Dutton |page=253 |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref> and by a cool and unshakeable scepticism.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pritchard |first1=William H. |year=1998 |title=Talking Back to Emily Dickinson and Other Essays |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IaGmwq4wAJsC&pg=PA49&dq=%22secure+voice+of+the+confirmed+skeptic%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik4euVparYAhXIZFAKHcUmCBgQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22secure%20voice%20of%20the%20confirmed%20skeptic%22&f=false |location=Amherst |publisher=University of Massachusetts Press |page=49 |isbn=1558491384 |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  They fascinate the reader through the huge zest for life they manifest.{{sfn|Marchand|1973|p=18}}  They share with his poems the characteristics of vigour and movement.  "Everything is said without reserve, without attenuation, savagely", wrote [[André Maurois]]; they "[sweep] the reader along in an irresistible onrush".  They repeat words as if they were rhymes, and have rhythms that resemble those of the poems apart from being more varied.{{sfn|Maurois|1936|p=xii}}  They share the outlook on life of Byron's more realistic poems, like ''[[Beppo (poem)|Beppo]]'', ''[[Don Juan (Byron)|Don Juan]]'' and ''[[The Vision of Judgment]]'', rather than the darkly romantic ''[[Childe Harold's Pilgrimage|Childe Harold]]'', ''[[Manfred]]'' and ''[[The Corsair]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lansdown |first1=Richard |year=2012 |title=The Cambridge Introduction to Byron |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8z7P0WFNUY8C&pg=PA48&dq=%22what+of+the+Byron+who+thrilled%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC8-2xqqrYAhWJYVAKHYblByIQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22what%20of%20the%20Byron%20who%20thrilled%22&f=false |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=48 |isbn=9780521111331 |access-date=27 November 2017 }}</ref>

==The number of letters==

Although Byron's life was cut short at the age of only 36, almost 3000 letters of his are known.{{sfn|Marchand|1981|p=1}}  There are three main reasons why that number is so large: one is simply the pleasure Byron took in composing them; another is the fact that Byron spent many years in self-imposed exile in Italy and Greece, which made it necessary for him to write to keep in touch with his friends in England; and finally, the sensational success of ''Childe Harold's Pilgrimage'' when Byron was only 23 turned him into a national and then international celebrity, making his letters valuable relics to be collected rather than thrown away.<ref>{{cite book |year=1927 |editor1-last=Collins |editor1-first=V. H. |title=Lord Byron in His Letters: Selections from His Letters and Journals |location=London |publisher=John Murray |page=vi }}</ref>

==Correspondents==

Byron's correspondents can be divided up into successive groups.  As a boy he wrote to his mother, his half-sister [[Augusta Leigh|Augusta]], and the family lawyer John Hanson.  At [[Southwell, Nottinghamshire|Southwell]] there were John Pigot and his sister [[Elizabeth Bridget Pigot|Elizabeth]].  Byron's friends at college included Scrope Davies, [[John Hobhouse, 1st Baron Broughton|John Cam Hobhouse]] and [[Francis Hodgson]].  With the publication of ''Childe Harold'' he became known to a new circle, the poets [[Robert Charles Dallas]], [[Thomas Moore]] and [[Samuel Rogers]], along with his banker [[Douglas Kinnaird]] and his publisher [[John Murray (1778–1843)|John Murray]].  Then there were the women who fell in love with him: [[Lady Caroline Lamb]], [[Frances Caroline Wedderburn-Webster|Lady Frances Webster]], [[Jane Harley, Countess of Oxford and Countess Mortimer|Lady Oxford]], and his future wife [[Lady Byron|Annabella Milbancke]]; also his confidante [[Lady Melbourne]].  A new group of friends in Switzerland included the poet [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]], Shelley's wife [[Mary Shelley|Mary]] and sister-in-law [[Claire Clairmont]].  Members of the Shelley circle with whom Byron corresponded included [[Thomas Medwin]], [[Edward Ellerker Williams|Edward Williams]] and his common-law wife [[Jane Williams|Jane]], [[Edward John Trelawny]], and the poet [[Leigh Hunt]].  In Venice there were Byron's lover [[Teresa, Contessa Guiccioli|Teresa Guiccioli]], her brother Gamba and husband Count Guiccioli, the British consul Richard Belgrave Hoppner, and Alexander Scott<ref>The Morgan Library, [https://www.themorgan.org/literary-historical/81465 Collection of autograph letters signed : Ravenna, to Alexander Scott, 1819 June 10 - Oct. 2].</ref><ref>Oliver Bradbury, [https://online.liverpooluniversitypress.co.uk/doi/10.3828/BJ.2001.6 "Come back to Venice, My Lord" : Alexander Scott's Letters to Lord Byron, in The Byron Journal, n° 29, 2001, p. 47-61].</ref>.  Finally, Byron's Greek adventure brought him into contact with a new circle: the rebel leader [[Alexandros Mavrokordatos|Prince Mavrokordatos]], the banker [[Samuel Barff]], and members of the [[London Philhellenic Committee]], including Colonel [[Leicester Stanhope, 5th Earl of Harrington|Leicester Stanhope]].{{sfn|Maurois|1936|pp=x-xi}}

==Editions==

In 1830, 6 years after his death, about 560 of Byron's letters were published by his friend Thomas Moore under the title ''Letters and Journals of Lord Byron: With Notices of his Life''.{{sfn|Lansdown|2015|p=xi}}  The next edition of the letters and journals appeared in six volumes in 1898-1901, edited by [[Rowland Prothero, 1st Baron Ernle|R. E. Prothero]] as part of a 13-volume ''Works''.  Prothero included nearly 1200 letters, conscientiously edited, though like Moore he excised all passages likely to offend 19th-century sensibilities.  A collection of about 350 unpublished letters was bequeathed by John Hobhouse's daughter Lady Dorchester to John Murray, who published them as ''Lord Byron’s Correspondence'' in 1922, in two volumes, though yet again in a bowdlerized form.  In 1950 [[Peter Quennell]] produced a selection of the letters, called ''Byron: A Self-Portrait'', of which 50 letters had not up to that point been published.{{sfn|Marchand|1973|p=24}}   In 1966 the American literary scholar [[Leslie A. Marchand]], having written a magisterial biography of Byron, began work on editing his letters.  The result, ''Byron's Letters and Journals'', appeared in 11 volumes plus an index volume between 1973 and 1982, with a final supplementary volume in 1994.  He was assisted in his work by the edition's publisher, John Murray VI, grandson of the earlier editor and great-great-grandson of Byron's own publisher.  Marchand's work included about 3000 letters, and it remains the reference edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://digital.nls.uk/jma/who/marchand/index.html |title=Leslie A Marchand (1900-1999) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=The John Murray Archive |publisher=National Library of Scotland |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  The first two volumes won the [[Modern Language Association]]'s [[James Russell Lowell Prize]] for 1974, the judges calling it "an outstanding achievement in humane editing".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674089419 |title=Byron's Letters and Journals, Volume II: ‘Famous in My Time’, 1810-1812 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2017 |publisher=Harvard University Press |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674089440&content=reviews |title=Byron's Letters and Journals, Volume IV: 'Wedlock's the Devil', 1814-1815 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2017 |publisher=Harvard University Press |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  In 1982 he followed this up with a one-volume selection of Byron's letters and journals.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burt |first1=Daniel S. |author-link1=Daniel Burt (author) |year=2001 |title=The Biography Book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jpFrgSAaKAUC&pg=PA54&dq=%22Marchand+has+chosen%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwizgrSNs6rYAhXSKlAKHamNBhsQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=%22Marchand%20has%20chosen%22&f=false |location=Westport, CT |publisher=Oryx Press |page=54 |isbn=1573562564 |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>  In 2015 Richard Lansdown published  another selection, which differed from Marchand's in being about twice the size and in attempting to cover Byron's whole life rather than just picking out the best letters.  Jeffery Vail called it "engrossing, moving, hilarious, and sometimes heartbreaking", and preferred it to the Marchand selection.<ref> {{cite news |last=Markovits |first=Benjamin |date=10 May 2015 |title=Review of ''Byron's Letters and Journals: A New Selection'' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/11591857/Byrons-Letters-and-Journals-aNewSelection-ed-by-Richard-Lansdown-review.html |work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal |last1=Vail |first1=Jeffery |date=2016 |title=Review of ''Byron's Letters and Journals: A New Selection'' |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/673669 |journal=Keats-Shelley Journal |volume=65 |page=173 |access-date=27 December 2017 }}</ref>

