{{Infobox NRHP | name = Harlan Hall | nrhp_type = | image = Harlan Hall in Marshall.jpg | caption = | location= 603 Locust St., [[Marshall, Illinois]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|23|22|N|87|41|42|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Illinois#USA | architect OR builder = | architecture = Italianate | added = November 29, 2001 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 01001309<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} [[File:Harlan Hall, Marshall, IL, US.jpg|right|thumb|Harlan Hall in 2015]] '''Harlan Hall''' is a historic [[opera house]] located at 603 Locust St. in [[Marshall, Illinois|Marshall]], [[Illinois]]. The opera house opened in 1872 to provide a venue for theatrical performances in Marshall. The building has an [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] design with tall, narrow windows, wide [[bracket (architecture)|bracket]]ed [[eave]]s, and a steeply sloping roof. Both local and traveling theatrical acts performed in the theater, which also hosted concerts, public meetings, and other events. The opera house had a [[livery stable]] on its first floor for its patrons' horses, an unusual feature for contemporary theaters. In 1904, B. F. Johnson purchased the building and converted it to a [[movie theater]]; while it still served as a civic auditorium, the building no longer showed theatrical performances after this point. The building has since held a [[Loyal Order of Moose|Moose Lodge]], and its first floor has been converted to a commercial space.<ref>{{cite web|last=Macey|first=Damian T.|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Harlan Hall|url=http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/pdfs/218417.pdf|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=March 10, 2014|date=June 28, 2001}}</ref>
The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on November 29, 2001.<ref name="nris"/>
